# Backend Architecture Rules

## 1. Architectural Style
The backend must follow Clean Architecture principles with strict separation of layers.

---

## 2. Layers and Responsibilities

### Domain Layer
- Contains business entities and core business rules
- Must not depend on any external framework or infrastructure
- Entities must be pure and framework-agnostic

### Application Layer
- Contains use cases (application services)
- Orchestrates domain entities
- Defines application-specific business flows
- Depends only on Domain layer

### Infrastructure Layer
- Contains external system implementations (DB, APIs, messaging)
- Implements interfaces defined in Domain or Application layers
- Must not contain business logic

### Presentation Layer
- Handles HTTP/controllers or API entry points
- Translates requests into application use cases
- Must be thin and contain no business logic

---

## 3. Dependency Rule
Dependencies must always point inward:
Presentation → Application → Domain  
Infrastructure → Domain/Application (via interfaces only)

---

## 4. Domain Entities
- Must contain core business logic
- Must be immutable where possible
- Must not depend on frameworks, ORMs, or external libraries

---

## 5. Application Services
- Must coordinate domain entities
- Must not contain infrastructure logic (DB, HTTP, external APIs)
- Must depend on abstractions (interfaces), not implementations

---

## 6. Contracts (Interfaces)
- All external dependencies must be abstracted via interfaces
- Interfaces define behavior, not implementation details
- Implementations live in Infrastructure layer

---

## 7. Dependency Injection Rule
- All dependencies must be injected via constructors or composition root
- No direct instantiation of infrastructure inside domain/application layers